holars pay homage to Robinson's later perspectives of the novel and a concluding postscript contains remembrances by his colleagues and students. This volume not only makes explicit the question of what it means to be human, a question Robinson invited students and colleagues to examine throughout his career, but it also illustrates the depth of the field and diversity of those who have been inspired by Robinson's work. Frankenstein and STEAM offers direction for continuing scholarship on the intersections of literature, science, and technology. Published by the University of Delaware Press. Distributed worldwide by Rutgers University Press.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aLiterature and science. 0aLiterature and technology. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  ascience, technology, engineering, art, math, mathematics, STEAM, literature, nineteenth-century studies, nineteenth-century, writing, editing, student, students, career, texts, essays.1 aBates, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBates, Brian.1 aChapin, Lisbeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChapin, Lisbeth.1 aCrafton, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrafton, Lisa.1 aHammerman, Robin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHammerman, Robin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHammerman, Robin.1 aMcCutcheon, Mark A.1 aMcCutcheon, Mark A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMekler, L. Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMekler, L. Adam.1 aWatters, Siobhan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWatters, Siobhan.1 aWolfson, Susan J.1 aWolfson, Susan J., econtributor.